Stormy Simon to Resign as Overstock President 
Lauded by Overstock founder as “a key contributor” to the retailer’s growthJuly 18, 2016, David Gill
 













 
Stormy SimonSALT LAKE CITY-Stormy Simon, president of Overstock.com, will resign her post no later than July 25 after an earlier announced leave of absence.
Simon is leaving to pursue other interests, according to an Overstock statement. She will remain on the online retailer’s board of directors until no later than Sept. 30.
She began a leave of absence from Overstock on June 6, for undisclosed reasons, according to a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Her responsibilities were divided among Acting CEO Mitch Edwards, Chief Revenue Officer Saum Noursalehi and Senior Vice President Brian Popelka—who will continue to exercise these roles as Simon prepares to leave the company, according to the company statement.








This is the second major change at the top of Overstock’s executive ranks this year. In April, Patrick Byrne, who founded Overstock in 1999 and who had been its CEO, took a medical leave of absence. Byrne has been battling hepatitis C, which he contracted in 1984 in China. In June, he returned to an active role on the board, although Edwards has continued as interim CEO.
Simon “has been a key contributor to Overstock’s evolution and growth from the early years, serving in a broad spectrum of roles and providing valuable leadership as president since 2014, and as a member of our board since 2011,” Byrne said.
Simon joined Overstock in 2001. “She has been a valuable member of the management team,” said Tom Forte, analyst with Maxim Group who covers Overstock. “She has been there a long time and filled a lot of roles. Today, Overstock is one of the largest e-commerce companies in the U.S.”
Over the past year, however, Overstock’s revenue growth has slowed, Forte noted. In addition, Wayfair has been taking market share from Overstock and other online retailers, particularly in home furnishings. “I could see this as a contributing factor to Stormy’s departure,” Forte said.
“While I will miss seeing my friends at Overstock on a daily basis, I am excited to focus my efforts on helping lead a new generation of entrepreneurs in developing a new sector of emerging markets,” Simon said.
 



 



 
David Gill | Senior Editor dgill@hfnmag.com
David Gill covers home textiles, small electrics housewares, personal-care products, cleaning products, mattresses, consumer electronics and major appliances. He also reports on retailers and writes about the business and financial side of both vendors and retailers. He has more than 30 years of experience in business journalism, and has worked for other publications and websites that cover consumer products from both the manufacturer and retailer sides. His outside interests include sports (he is a big fan of the New York teams and of British soccer), cooking, movies and theater. He occasionally enjoys a good cigar as well.
 

